    "created_at": "2015-02-17T05:30:21Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-02-17T05:30:21Z",
    "body": "@alexcrichton My point is not whether Rust's `File` should use a file descriptor from MSVCRT or `HANDLE` from Win32 API and closing this issue is invalid.  Let me repeat relevant points from my original comment:\n\n> The symptom is, `notepad.exe` cannot correctly read text files produced by `io::File`. It is associated to `.TXT` files on Windows by default.\n> \n> To our (un?)luck, the `cmd.exe` console starts a new line with only an `LF` character.\n> \n> Java and .NET address this issue by defining utilities to specifically handle \"stream of characters/texts\" in addition to those for byte stream:\n> - https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/io/Reader.html\n> - http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.io.textreader.aspx\n",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
